Introduction¶

In this project, I will investigate the TMDb movie dataset. This dataset contain 10.866 movies informations that was released between the years 1960 and 2015.

The dataset has the following collumns:

> id - The movie's ID.
> imdb_id - The movie's ID used in IMDB.
> popularity - A numeric quantity specifying the popularity of the movie.
> budget - The movie's budget in US dollars.
> revenue - The movie's revenue in US dollars.
> original_title - The title of the movie.
> cast - A list of actors who worked in movie.
> homepage - A link to the movie's homepage.
> director - The movie's director.
> tagline - The movie's tagline.
> keywords - The keywords or tags related to the movie.
> overview - A movie description.
> runtime - The running time of the movie in minutes.
> genres - The movie's genre (could be many genres listed).
> production_companies - The company that produced the movie.
> release_date - The movie's release date.
> vote_count - A numeric quantity specifying the count of votes the movie received.
> vote_average - The average rating the movie recieved.
> release_year - The year that the movie was released.
> budget_adj - The budget corrected by the 2010 inflation in US dollars .
> revenue_adj - The revenue corrected by the 2010 inflation in US dollars.

This project's main objective is to perform exploratory data analysis using pandas, numpy, seaborn and matplotlib python libraries.

Questions¶

  1. What are the highest revenue movies?
  2. What is the average revenue of a movie over the years?
  3. What are the highest budget movies?
  4. What is the average budget of a movie over the years?
  5. What are the highest profit movies?
  6. What is the average profit of a movie over the years?
  7. Which month had the most movies releases?
  8. Which year had the most movies releases?
  9. Which genres have the most movies released?
  10. What is the average length of a movie over the years?
  11. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

Too many zeros in revenue and budget columns¶

The revenue and the budget columns have a lot of zeros. These zero can bias our analysis and comparison. To correct this we could categorize the movies according to the budget into AAA, AA, and A. That way we would apply the average budget according to the movie (AAA = large budget; AA = medium; A = indie movie). But to do that we would need to study every movie that is without budget and define what AAA is each year. Another solution may be to remove the rows that are zeros in budget and revenue. However there are too many lines (6016 movies with zero in revenue; 5696 movies with zero in budget).

For now, let's just replace the zeros for NaN (Not a Number) in Data Cleaning section and continue with the analysis.

In [23]:
# Constructing a DataFrame to filter, sort and cut the 20 movies by revenue
df_revenue = pd.DataFrame(df["revenue"].sort_values(ascending = False))[:20]
df_revenue["original_title"] = df["original_title"]

# Setting up the figure
plt.figure(figsize = (20,10))
sns.set_color_codes("dark")

# Plotting
sns.barplot(x = "revenue", y = "original_title", data = df_revenue, color = "b", label = "Revenue", alpha = 0.6)

# Setting up the title and axes label
plt.title("The Highest Movies in Revenue", fontsize = 14)
plt.xlabel("Revenue (US Dollars)", fontsize = 10)
plt.ylabel(" ")
plt.legend();

Research Question 5: What are the highest profit movies?¶

In order to calculate the highest profit movies, we need to create a new column for each movie. Let's call this new column "profit". Let's define the profit of a movie like the total revenue minus the budget.

In [27]:
# Creating the new column
df["profit"] = df["revenue"] - df["budget"]

Research Question 9: Which genres have the most movies released?¶

In [36]:
# Concatenating genres from all movies given the separator => |
df_genres = df["genres"].str.cat(sep = "|")

# Splitting the total value and store
df_genres = pd.Series(df_genres.split("|"))

# Counting the genres
genres_resume = df_genres.value_counts(ascending = False)

# Setting up the figure
plt.figure(figsize = (15,5))
sns.set_color_codes("dark")

# Plotting
genres_resume.plot.bar(color = "b", alpha = 0.6)

# Setting up the title and axes label
plt.title("The Genres movies more released", fontsize = 14)
plt.xlabel("Genres", fontsize = 10)
plt.ylabel("Number of Movies", fontsize = 10);

The Drama was the genre with more movies released (4.760 movies), followed by Comedy (3.793 movies) and Thriller (2.907 movies). Remember that a movie can be classified with more than one genre.

The heat map above shows in the revenue line the correlation between the revenue and the others columns.

We can see a higher positive correlation between revenue and profit (0,98), vote_count (0,76), budget (0,69) and popularity (0,63).

A lower positive correlation can be noted between revenue and runtime (0,24), vote_average (0,21) and release_year (0,12).

A weak negative correlation can be seen between revenue and id (-0,041).

sns.scatterplot(x = "revenue", y = "budget", data = df, color = "g", alpha = 0.6)

# Setting up the title and axes label
plt.title("Correlation: Revenue x Budget", fontsize = 14)
plt.xlabel("Revenue (US Dollars)")
plt.ylabel("Budget (US Dollars)");

We can consider that if a company has approved a high budget for making a movie, it expects to receive high revenue. However, this does not always happen. It is a high bet.

Conclusions¶

  1. What are the highest revenue movies?

    The highest revenue movies are: Avatar, Star Wars: The Force Awakens, Titanic, The Avengers, ...


  2. What is the average revenue of a movie over the years?

    The average revenue of a movie over the years has significantly increasing. Despite severe oscillations in 1965 and 1977. Reaching the top in 2015.


  3. What are the highest budget movies?

    The highest budget movies are: The Warrior's Way, Pirates of the Caribbean: On Stranger Tides, Pirates of the Caribbean: At World's End, Avengers: Age of Ultron, ...


  4. What is the average budget of a movie over the years?

    The average budget of a movie over the years had increased strong until 1997, stabilizing until 1998, when started decreased. In 2003 and 2010 the budget increased quickly again, but fell again, keeping the downward trend.


  5. What are the highest profit movies?

    The highest profit movies are: Avatar, Star Wars: The Force Awakens, Titanic, Jurassic World, ...


  6. What is the average profit of a movie over the years?

    The average profit of a movie over the years grew strongly in line with revenue. The chart shows severe oscillations with a growing tendency, reaching the top in 2015.


  7. Which month had the most movies releases?

    September was the month with more movies released (1.331 movies), followed by October (1.153 movies) and December (985 movies).


  8. Which year had the most movies releases?

    The 2014 was the year with more movies released (700 movies), followed by 2013 (659 movies) and 2015 (629 movies).


  9. Which genres have the most movies released?

    The Drama was the genre with more movies released (4.760 movies), followed by Comedy (3.793 movies) and Thriller (2.907 movies). Remember that a movie can be classified with more than one genre.


  10. What is the average length of a movie over the years?

    The average length of a movie has been falling over the years.


  11. What kinds of properties are associated with movies that have high revenues?

    The heat map shows in the revenue line the correlation between the revenue and the others columns.

    We can see a higher positive correlation between revenue and profit (0,98), vote_count (0,76), budget (0,69) and popularity (0,63).

    A lower positive correlation can be noted between revenue and runtime (0,24), vote_average (0,21) and release_year (0,12).

    A weak negative correlation can be seen between revenue and id (-0,041).
